<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-599-452  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 599 452.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  Sept 4 1989 v6 n35 p13(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Trio to throw hats in notebook PC ring. (vendors announce newDOS-compatible laptops) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Grossman, Evan O.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Poqet Computer, GRiD Systems and Toshiba America are all expectedto announce DOS-compatible laptops.andP;  Poqet Computer's $1,995computer includes MS-DOS 3.3 in ROM, weights 1 pound, measures 8inches by 4 inches, and has an 80-character-by-25-lineColor-Graphics-Adapter-compatible display.andP;  GRiD's system is an80386-based notebook computer weighing less than 5 pounds andmeasuring 9 inches by 6 inches with a mini-floppy-disk drive.andO;Toshiba's notebook computer weighs less than 6 pounds, has a3.5-inch floppy-disk drive, a full-sized keyboard and a backlitLCD screen.andP;  The entrance of new players into the DOS-compatiblelaptop market will increase as vendors sense a market opportunity,so vendors are looking for ways to differentiate their products.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Poqet Computer Corp. (product introduction)Grid Systems Corp. (product introduction)Toshiba America Inc. (product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionLaptop computersCompatible HardwareMSDOSMarket Entry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>By Evan O. GrossmanandM;NEC Home Electronics (U.S.A.) Inc.'s UltraLite laptop and Zenith DataSystems' MinisPort computer will be joined this fall by at least three otherlightweight DOS-compatible laptops, according to analysts, vendors andsources close to the firms.andM;Poqet Computer Corp. plans to announce next week a 1-pound system, accordingto officials at the Sunnyvale, Calif., firm.andP;  GRiD Systems Corp. and ToshibaAmerica Inc. are also expected to enter the market before the end of theyear, sources close to those companies said recently.andM;The $1,995 Poqet computer comes with MS-DOS 3.3 in ROM, measures 8 inches by4 inches by less than 1 inch thick when closed, and has an80-character-by-25-line Color Graphics Adapter (CGA)-compatible display.andP;  Thekeyboard is not full-sized, yet is fully functional, officials claim.andM;The lightweight GRiD system is one of three GRiD laptops expected byComdex/Fall from the Fremont, Calif., company, sources close to the firmsaid.andM;GRiD's 80C86-based notebook computer, called the &quot;tablet&quot; by some sources,will weigh less than 5 pounds, sport a minifloppy-disk drive and featuredimensions of 9 inches by 6 inches, according to sources.andM;&quot;We think it'll make quite a splash,&quot; said one source inside the company.andM;Toshiba is currently selling a notebook-sized computer in Japan that weighsless than 6 pounds, and comes equipped with a 3-1/2-inch floppy-disk driveand a full-sized keyboard and backlit LCD screen.andM;The notebook-sized laptop arena will gain new players this year as vendorssense a market opportunity, said Bruce Stephen, an analyst at InternationalData Corp., a market researcher in Framingham, Mass.andM;To seize that opportunity, vendors are looking for ways to differentiatetheir products.andM;&quot;It comes down to size, weight and battery life,&quot; said Gerry Purdy, Poqet'sdirector of marketing.andM;For example, while the Zenith system includes a 2-inch floppy-disk drive, theNEC and Poqet machines have slots for memory cards.andP;  Weights vary from theMinisPort's 5.9 pounds to the Poqet unit's 1 pound.andM;Meanwhile, the NEC UltraLite, which started the new market, could undergo aface-lift in the near future, sources said.andM;&quot;NEC has to make some changes, at least in battery life, to stay competitivewith Zenith,&quot; said an analyst who asked not to be identified.andO;</TEXT></DOC>